Installation
************

@{u}WARNING!@{uu} You need AmigaDos 2.04 or greater to use Badger!

@{b}Badger@{ub} is very simple to install. Just copy it to some suitable place,
for instance @{i}WBStartup@{ui} if you want it there.

@{b}Badger@{ub} uses a configuration file: @{i}S:Badger-Config@{ui}. It doesn't have
to exist for @{b}Badger@{ub} to start, it will just have an empty list. You
shouldn't touch the file directly but rather edit it with @{b}Badger@{ub}.
(See @{" Usage " Link "Usage"})

@{u}NOTE!@{uu} If you have an old config file you must delete it.
      @{b}Badger@{ub} v1.1 uses a different format.

@{b}Badger@{ub} v1.1 automatically unsnapshots icons so there is no longer any
need for a special drawer with unsnapshot icons, but it can still be practical
to group your icons in one place.

@EndNode

@Node "Usage" "Badger.guide/Usage"
@Next "Changes"
@Prev "Installation"
@Toc "Main"

Usage
*****

Using @{b}Badger@{ub} isn't any more difficult than moving files beetween two drawers.
Just drag any amount of files on @{b}Badger@{ub}'s icon and the rest goes by itself.
Unless, of course a file doesn't fit any of the patterns. In that case a file
requester will come up which you can chose an appropriate icon with.

The configuration of @{b}Badger@{ub} v1.1 works quite different than before.
Instead of having a icon filename for each pattern there are now two lists,
one for the patterns and one for the available icons. Each pattern has a
link to an icon.

Double-click on @{b}Badger@{ub}'s icon to see it's brand new enhanced user interface. 
To add a new pattern first press the @{i}'NEW'@{ui} button below the @{i}'Patterns'@{ui}
listview. Then enter the pattern in the string and press return.

If the icon file you want for that pattern is already in the @{i}Icons'@{ui} listview
just click on it and it will be linked to the new pattern. Otherwise press the
'@{i}NEW@{ui}' button below @{i}'Icons'@{ui}. You can enter the file name by hand or use the
filerequester by pressing @{i}'GET'@{ui}.

To link an existing pattern with an existing icon file name just select the
pattern then select the icon name. When you select a pattern the corresponding
icon name (if any) gets selected.

The buttons below are pretty straightforward. @{i}'QUIT'@{ui} removes @{b}Badger@{ub}.
@{i}'SAVE'@{ui} saves the config and closes the window while @{i}'HIDE'@{ui} just closes
the window.
@EndNode

@Node "Changes" "Badger.guide/Changes"
@Next "Contact"
@Prev "Usage"
@Toc "Main"

Changes
*******

New in version 1.1:

This is the first version submitted to Fred Fish.
New user interface whith two listviews.
The old was unpractical and a little unstable.
This also forced a new format for the config file.

I found out that nonproportional fonts made the font-
adaptive GUI look weird, so I changed it to use the
system instead of the screen font.

Removed 'About' window and replaced with an requester.
It didn't fill any practical function and increased
the size of the program. Version 1.1 is actually a
little smaller than 1.0!

@EndNode

